In [[arbitration]], the '''repeat-player effect''' is a proposition that, outside of the [[collective bargaining]] context, employers attain more favorable outcomes in arbitration.<ref name=bingham>{{cite journal|last=Bingham|first=Lisa|title=Employment Arbitration: The Repeat Player Effect|journal=Employee Rights and Employment Policy Journal|year=1997|volume=1|pages=189–220|ssrn=1324411}}</ref>  Factors contributing to the repeat-player effect include employers' having more information to gain an advantage in the arbitrator selection process, as well as influence on arbitrators, who may want to rule in the employer's favor to be selected in future arbitrations.<ref name=colvin>{{cite journal|last=Colvin|first=Alexander J. S.|title=An Empirical Study of Employment Arbitration: Case Outcomes and Processes|journal=Journal of Empirical Legal Studies|date=1 March 2011|volume=8|issue=1|pages=1–23|doi=10.1111/j.1740-1461.2010.01200.x|url=http://digitalcommons.ilr.cornell.edu/articles/577}}</ref>

